## 5. Database Schema (Supabase)

Defined in `supabase/schema.sql` (idempotent; safe to re-run). All tables live in
`public` and reference `auth.users(id)` with `on delete cascade`.

### `public.meetings`
| column        | type          | notes                                    |
|---------------|---------------|------------------------------------------|
| id            | uuid PK       | `default gen_random_uuid()`              |
| user_id       | uuid NOT NULL | FK → `auth.users(id)`, indexed           |
| title         | text NOT NULL | `default 'New Recording'`                |
| summary       | text          |                                          |
| action_items  | jsonb         | `default '[]'`                           |
| segments      | jsonb         | `default '[]'` (speaker/text pairs)      |
| created_at    | timestamptz   | `default now()`                          |

### `public.speakers` (scaffolding)
| column        | type          | notes                          |
|---------------|---------------|--------------------------------|
| id            | uuid PK       |                                |
| user_id       | uuid NOT NULL | FK → `auth.users(id)`, indexed |
| name          | text NOT NULL |                                |
| meetings      | jsonb         | `default '[]'`                 |
| mentions      | jsonb         | `default '{}'`                 |
| action_items  | jsonb         | `default '[]'`                 |
| created_at    | timestamptz   | `default now()`                |

### `public.calendar_events` (scaffolding)
| column      | type          | notes                                   |
|-------------|---------------|-----------------------------------------|
| id          | uuid PK       |                                         |
| user_id     | uuid NOT NULL | FK → `auth.users(id)`, indexed          |
| meeting_id  | uuid          | FK → `public.meetings(id)` cascade      |
| title       | text NOT NULL |                                         |
| due_date    | timestamptz   |                                         |
| assignee    | text          |                                         |
| created_at  | timestamptz   | `default now()`                         |

TypeScript shapes mirroring these tables live in `lib/data.ts` (`Meeting`,
`Speaker`, `CalendarEvent`) alongside demo fixtures.

---

## 6. Authentication Flow (Supabase Auth + RLS)

**Method:** email + password (default) and magic link, via Supabase Auth.

### Sign up / Sign in (web)
1. User submits credentials on `/sign-up` or `/sign-in`.
2. `useAuth()` (`components/auth-provider.tsx`) calls
   `supabase.auth.signUp` / `signInWithPassword` / `signInWithOtp`.
3. On success the session is persisted client-side (localStorage) and
   `onAuthStateChange` updates context. The user is routed to `/success`.
4. Magic-link / email-confirmation redirects land on `/auth/callback`, which
   finalizes the session and forwards into the app.

### Route protection
- `components/auth-gate.tsx` wraps the `(app)` group.
  - If Supabase is **not configured** → open demo mode (renders children).
  - If configured and `loading` → spinner.
  - If configured, no user, and route is not public → redirect to `/sign-in`.
  - Public routes: `/sign-in`, `/sign-up`, `/auth/callback`.

### API authorization (two-layer ownership)
1. **Application layer** — API routes use the **service-role** key (which
   bypasses RLS) and therefore enforce ownership explicitly: every request is
   validated via `getUserFromRequest`, and every query filters by `user_id`.
2. **Database layer (RLS)** — `supabase/schema.sql` enables RLS and adds
   `select/insert/update/delete` policies of the form `auth.uid() = user_id` on
   `meetings`, `speakers`, and `calendar_events`. This protects any client that
   talks to Supabase directly with the anon key.

### Extension auth
The extension stores the user's Supabase **access token** in
`chrome.storage.local` (key `afterthought_access_token`) and sends it as a
`Bearer` header on upload. Tokens are surfaced to the user via the
"Extension access" card on `/settings` (`getAccessToken()`).

---

## 7. Chrome Extension Architecture

A framework-less Manifest V3 extension in `extension/`.

- `manifest.json` — MV3. `permissions: tabs, activeTab, storage, microphone`.
  `host_permissions: http://localhost:3000/*`, `https://afterthought.vercel.app/*`.
  Background service worker (`type: module`), popup = `popup.html`.
- `popup.html` / `popup.css` / `popup.js` — Popup UI. Lets the user save/clear
  their Supabase access token (persisted to `chrome.storage.local`) and start a
  recording session by asking the background worker to open the recording tab.
- `background.js` — Service worker. Handles two messages:
  - `open-recording-tab` → opens `recording.html` in a new tab.
  - `upload-recording` → `uploadRecording(blob)`: reads the stored token, POSTs
    the audio Blob to `http://localhost:3000/api/transcribe` with
    `Content-Type: audio/webm` and `Authorization: Bearer <token>`; surfaces a
    clear error on missing token or `401`.
- `recording.html` / `recording.js` — Dedicated recording page. Uses
  `navigator.mediaDevices.getUserMedia({ audio:true })` + `MediaRecorder`,
  collects chunks into an `audio/webm` Blob, sends it to the background worker,
  and on success redirects to `http://localhost:3000/recording/<id>`.
- `content.js` — Minimal content script (logs presence only).

**Note:** `manifest.json` references `popup.js` (the shipped vanilla JS popup),
while `scripts/build.js` references a `popup.tsx` source that is not present.

---

## 8. PWA Architecture

- `next.config.mjs` wraps the Next config with `next-pwa` (`withPWAInit`):
  - `dest: "public"`, `disable: NODE_ENV === "development"` (service worker is
    generated only for production builds), `images.unoptimized: true`,
    and `turbopack.root` pinned to the project directory.
- `public/manifest.json` — Web App Manifest: name "AfterThought",
  `display: standalone`, `start_url: /`, `background_color`/`theme_color`
  `#0c0d12`, icons (`/icon-light-32x32.png`, `/apple-icon.png`).
- Installable on desktop/mobile; the production service worker provides caching
  for offline-capable shell loading.

---

## 9. Data Flow

### Extension → Backend
```
recording.js (MediaRecorder → audio/webm Blob)
   → background.js upload-recording message
   → fetch POST /api/transcribe
        headers: Content-Type: audio/webm, Authorization: Bearer <access_token>
   → 200 { ok:true, id }  → redirect /recording/<id>
   → 401 → "Unauthorized, save a fresh token"
```

### Backend → Supabase
```
/api/transcribe (POST)
   → getUserFromRequest(req)  // validate bearer token → User
   → supabaseAdmin().from('meetings').insert({ id, user_id, title, summary, action_items, segments })
GET routes (/api/meetings, /api/meeting/[id], /api/speakers, /api/calendar)
   → supabaseAdmin().from(<table>).select('*').eq('user_id', user.id)
```

### Supabase → Frontend
```
Dashboard / detail pages
   → authFetch('/api/...')  // attaches Bearer token from supabaseBrowser() session
   → Route Handler returns user-scoped rows
   → React state renders meetings / insights / speakers / calendar / templates
```

### AI Pipeline (placeholder)
```
/api/transcribe currently returns hard-coded:
   segments = [ {speaker, text}, ... ]
   summary  = "placeholder summary"
   actionItems = [ ... ]
Future: audio → STT (e.g. Whisper) → LLM (GPT/Claude) → summary, action items,
speaker diarization, then fan out to lib/email.ts, lib/calendar.ts, lib/speakers.ts.
```

